snippet.textDisplay: This is democracy vs autocracy in essence. Democracy is slow to react, but improves solutions to urgent problems over time and gets it right eventually. On the other hand, autocracy is fast to react but often backs itself into a corner because of pride, internal politics, and tunnel vision.

snippet.textDisplay:
@P D
It is, democracy is slow to start, but quick to adapt while autocracy is quick to start, but slow to adapt.
Like I said in my earlier post, the reason is because Supreme Leader want to show off and thus everyone start right away at his command, but once the situation change and things turn out different as the result, do you want to question the leader? The same reason why there is a Sparrow Campaign under Mao.
Do you really think nobody in China during that time to know about the ecosystem where you killed all the birds and nothing bad will happen? The answer is noone dare to speak up and said otherwise to make the leader lose face.

Throughout China's history, you can see many of this examples where Emperor "IS NEVER WRONG" because anyone who even said otherwise would challenge the authority and power of the leader. 
So from the start, if the leader said something like ZeroCovid and it means ZEROCOVID no matter the costs. It doesn't if millions of died in the process (Mao's examples) or science or things changes or whatever, it will remain the same since noone even willing to question the "SUPEREME LEADER".
